          "feedback": "Exactly right. Browsers cache DNS results and can reuse existing connections, so a repeat visit can skip straight past the lookup and handshake steps that ate up time on the first visit.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "The browser found the site's DNS entry and connection details already cached from before."
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Not quite — TLS negotiation happens per connection, and while session resumption can speed it up, it doesn't disappear entirely just because you've visited before.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The browser skipped the TLS handshake since HTTPS sites only encrypt data once ever."
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The browser doesn't compress outgoing requests to speed up the server's response — that's not how this works.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The browser compressed the HTML response before sending it to the server."
        },
        {
          "feedback": "There's no indication the server itself changed hardware — the speed boost is happening on the browser's side of the lifecycle.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The web server used a faster machine to process her repeat visit."
